<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Tannin Structure to Protein Density</strong> - Cabernet Sauvignon's high tannin levels (from thick grape skins and oak aging) require substantial proteins to soften them. Prime rib, ribeye, and lamb shoulder work perfectly because their fat content and protein density literally bind with tannins, creating a smooth, balanced mouthfeel. Avoid lean proteins like chicken breast or fish, which will make the wine taste harsh and astringent.</li>

  <li><strong>Embrace Bold, Umami-Rich Flavors</strong> - Cabernet's intense cassis and dark fruit profile can overpower delicate dishes. Instead, pair with foods high in umami compounds: aged Parmigiano-Reggiano, mushroom risotto with porcini, or dry-aged beef. These glutamate-rich foods enhance the wine's savory complexity while complementing its earthy, tobacco-like secondary notes from oak aging.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Regional Food Pairings for Terroir Harmony</strong> - Bordeaux Cabernet blends shine with classic French preparations like côte de bœuf with marrow bones, while Napa Valley Cabernets pair beautifully with barbecued brisket or grilled portobello mushrooms. The shared terroir creates natural flavor bridges—Bordeaux's mineral backbone complements herbs de Provence, while Napa's ripe fruit intensity matches bold American barbecue spices.</li>

  <li><strong>Account for Oak Treatment in Your Pairing</strong> - Heavily oaked Cabernets (especially new American oak) develop vanilla, coconut, and spice notes that pair exceptionally with grilled or smoked meats. The char on a grilled steak echoes the toasted oak flavors. Conversely, unoaked or lightly oaked versions work better with cleaner preparations like herb-crusted lamb or simple roasted vegetables with rosemary.</li>

  <li><strong>Balance Acidity Levels with Sauce Selection</strong> - Cabernet Sauvignon's moderate acidity (typically 6-7 g/L) means it needs slight acidity support from food. Red wine reductions, tomato-based sauces, or balsamic glazes provide this lift without overwhelming the wine. Cream-based sauces will flatten the wine's structure, while overly acidic accompaniments like citrus marinades will create an unpleasant clash.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Pairing with Wine Age and Development</strong> - Young, tannic Cabernets (under 5 years) need robust, fatty foods like braised short ribs or aged cheddar to tame their astringency. Mature Cabernets (10+ years) develop tertiary flavors of leather, cedar, and dried herbs that pair beautifully with more refined dishes like duck confit or wild mushroom tart, where the wine's complexity can shine without being overwhelmed.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Herbs and Spices as Flavor Bridges</strong> - Cabernet's herbal undertones from pyrazines (bell pepper compounds) and oak aging create natural affinities with specific seasonings. Rosemary, thyme, and black pepper amplify the wine's earthy qualities, while coffee rubs or cocoa-based mole sauces complement its dark fruit concentration and roasted oak notes.</li>

  <li><strong>Don't Overlook Vegetarian Power Pairings</strong> - While Cabernet is famous with red meat, its structure works brilliantly with hearty plant-based dishes. Grilled eggplant with balsamic reduction, lentil and mushroom shepherd's pie, or roasted beets with goat cheese provide enough earthiness and substance to complement the wine's intensity without requiring animal proteins.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What cuts of beef pair best with Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rich, marbled cuts like ribeye, prime rib, and New York strip are ideal matches for Cabernet Sauvignon's bold tannins and concentrated fruit flavors. The wine's structure cuts through the fat while complementing the meat's savory umami compounds. For best results, opt for cuts that can be grilled, roasted, or braised to develop deep, caramelized flavors that echo the wine's complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair Cabernet Sauvignon with fish or seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While unconventional, Cabernet Sauvignon can work with meaty fish like tuna, salmon, or swordfish when prepared with bold seasonings or red wine reductions. The key is matching the wine's intensity with equally robust preparations—think blackened salmon or tuna steaks with herb crusts. Avoid delicate white fish, as the wine's tannins will overwhelm subtle seafood flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What vegetables complement Cabernet Sauvignon's flavor profile?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Earthy vegetables like portobello mushrooms, roasted root vegetables, and grilled eggplant harmonize beautifully with Cabernet's earthy undertones and dark fruit character. Vegetables with natural umami—such as roasted tomatoes, caramelized onions, and bell peppers—enhance the wine's savory complexity. Avoid light, delicate vegetables that can't stand up to the wine's bold structure.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve different foods with young versus aged Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young Cabernets with firm tannins pair best with fatty, protein-rich foods like grilled steaks or aged cheeses that can soften the wine's astringency. Mature Cabernets with softer tannins and developed tertiary flavors work wonderfully with more nuanced dishes like braised short ribs, wild game, or mushroom-based preparations. The wine's evolution from primary fruit to complex earth and leather notes requires different food partnerships.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing food with Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is pairing Cabernet with delicate or lightly seasoned dishes that get overwhelmed by the wine's bold tannins and intense flavor concentration. Many people also serve the wine too warm, which amplifies alcohol heat and makes food pairings seem unbalanced. Always ensure your dishes have enough richness and flavor intensity to complement, not compete with, this powerful wine style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which cheeses work best with Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Aged, hard cheeses like aged Cheddar, Gouda, and Parmigiano-Reggiano provide excellent textural and flavor matches for Cabernet's structure and complexity. Blue cheeses like Roquefort create exciting contrast pairings where the wine's tannins balance the cheese's pungent saltiness. Avoid soft, mild cheeses like fresh mozzarella or Brie, which lack the intensity to stand up to Cabernet's bold character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good vegetarian main dishes for Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Hearty vegetarian dishes like eggplant parmigiana, stuffed portobello caps, or lentil-based preparations with rich tomato sauces pair excellently with Cabernet Sauvignon. The key is incorporating umami-rich ingredients like aged cheeses, roasted tomatoes, mushrooms, and herbs that can match the wine's intensity. Grilled or roasted preparation methods that develop caramelized flavors work particularly well with Cabernet's oak and dark fruit characteristics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do different Cabernet Sauvignon regions affect food pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley Cabernets with their ripe fruit and oak integration pair beautifully with grilled meats and bold American cuisine, while Bordeaux blends with their earthier profile complement more traditional European dishes like coq au vin or braised lamb. Australian Cabernets with eucalyptus notes work well with herb-crusted meats, and Chilean versions with their bright acidity can handle slightly spicier preparations than their Californian counterparts.</p>
  </div>
